Digits




IBM’s Rometty Bets on Consumer-Product Partnerships






By

Robert McMillan


Robert McMillan
The Wall Street Journal
BiographyRobert McMillan
@bobmcmillan
therealrobertmcmillan
robert.mcmillan@wsj.com



 and Don Clark


 and Don Clark
The Wall Street Journal
Biography and Don Clark
@donal888
www.facebook.com/DonClark
Don.Clark@wsj.com




                    Jan 7, 2016 12:23 am  ET
                  


International Business Machines Corp. is pivoting back to the consumer market it abandoned more than a decade ago when it spun off its PC business. The company aims to be a player in the emerging world of connected kitchen appliances and fitness monitors, among other products.
The plan is to use IBM’s artificial intelligence and data analytics technology to make such devices more useful, according to CEO Virginia “Ginni” Rometty. Ms. Rometty made her pitch on Wednesday to attendees at CES, the annual Las Vegas technology convention where many of these next-gen products were unveiled this week.



