Business Day

A C.E.O.’s Support System, a k a Husband



Common Sense 
By                     
 JAMES B. STEWART
 
NOV. 4, 2011




Continue reading the main story
Share This Page

Continue reading the main story










Photo






Virginia M. Rometty, newly named as chief of I.B.M., has a husband with the time and flexibility to support her career.

Credit
            Graham Carlow        



Here’s to Mark Rometty.Mr. Rometty is a principal investor in the Bam Oil Company, where he’s listed as treasurer and secretary and, when I called, answered the phone. He’s also married to Virginia Rometty, the new C.E.O.-designate and first woman tapped to head I.B.M., a company that not only ranks 18th in the Fortune 500, but stands as a symbol of American managerial prowess. Acquaintances say the intensely private Mr. Rometty deserves tremendous credit for pursuing a career that gave him the time and flexibility to support his wife’s ascension to the pinnacle of global business — as, for that matter, do the vast majority of C.E.O. spouses of both genders. Still, the C.E.O. husband remains a rarity in American business.When I reached Mr. Rometty this week at his Florida office, he was emphatic that this was a subject he didn’t want to discuss. Nor did Ms. Rometty, who was logging some of the millions of miles she travels every year visiting I.B.M. customers all over the globe.An I.B.M. spokesman said both were eager to preserve as much privacy as possible, and who can blame them? All he said was that both enjoyed scuba diving and Broadway plays and that they divided their time between homes in New York and Bonita Springs, Fla. They met when both were enrolled in the General Motors Institute embarking on business careers and have been married for 32 years.The Romettys aren’t the only couple reluctant to discuss the husband’s role in his wife’s success. There’s still a social stigma for the stay-at-home or less successful husband that women don’t face. And management experts say that that has to change if women are going to be represented in the top jobs at a level commensurate with their numbers and talent.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Asked at a Barnard College conference what men could do to help advance women’s leadership, Rosabeth Moss Kanter, a professor at Harvard Business School and author of the landmark “Men and Women of the Corporation,” answered, “The laundry.” Continue reading the main story







Advertisement

Continue reading the main story





“Women are not going to say, ‘My husband is not as successful as he could have been because he’s been supporting me,’ ” Ms. Kanter told me this week. “It would be seen as putting him down. But when the shoe is on the other foot, men say, ‘She really helped me.’ People say, ‘Isn’t it wonderful that he has someone who allows him to focus on his work?’ This is culturally valued.”Statistics suggest that aspirants to America’s top corporate jobs had better have a spouse, partner or someone else willing to be devoted to the aspirant’s career. “How do you compete without a spouse? Basically, you can’t,” Richard Zweigenhaft said. Mr. Zweigenhaft is professor of psychology at Guilford College in North Carolina and the co-author (with G. William Domhoff) of “The New C.E.O.’s,” a study of women and minorities who are chief executives (Rowman & Littlefield, 2011).The overwhelming number of American C.E.O.’s of both genders are married, and most, like Ms. Rometty, have been for many years. Divorce at this level is comparatively rare. Mr. Zweigenhaft and Mr. Domhoff studied all 28 women who had held or currently hold the post of chief executive of a Fortune 500 company (Ms. Rometty will be No. 29). Twenty-six were married, one was divorced and only one had never married. “How many had house husbands? We don’t really know, but there are certainly some who fit that pattern,” Mr. Zweigenhaft said. “Many of the women C.E.O.’s said they could not have succeeded without the support of their husbands, helping with the children, the household chores, and showing a willingness to move.”Eighteen of the 28 women had children. While impressive, that’s a far lower rate than the 87 percent of married women in the population at large who have children of their own, according to Census data.Ms. Rometty and her husband have no children. Ms. Kanter said she didn’t want to comment specifically about Ms. Rometty, whom she knows, but said “whether to have kids is a major question couples have to face.” She added: “It’s been easier for male executives to feel great about having kids, because in the traditional division of labor, it’s the wives’ responsibility. We haven’t moved that far towards the idea that men should do the same.”
Newsletter Sign Up
Continue reading the main story

  


