Not you?
Privacy Policy
Opt out or contact us anytime




When he announced Ms. Rometty’s selection, I.B.M.’s chief executive, Sam Palmisano, told The Times that “Ginni got it because she deserved it. It’s got zero to do with progressive social policies.” He didn’t say anything about Mr. Rometty, but Ms. Rometty credits her husband with a crucial insight that helped shape her corporate ambitions.“Early in my career, I can remember being offered a big job,” she told a Fortune magazine conference on women and careers last month. “I right away said, ‘You know what? I’m not ready for this job. I need more time, I need more experience and then I could really do it well.’ And so I said to him, ‘I need to go home and think about it.’ ...— And my husband at the time, as usual, I’m blah-blah-blahing, and he’s just sitting there. And as I’m telling him about this, and I told him I would get back to them tomorrow. And he said to me, he looked at me, and he just looked at me and he said, ‘Do you think a man would have ever answered that question that way?’ And I sort of sat there — and it taught me a lesson. And he said, “I know you, you go do it, you’re going to — six months you’re going to be bored.’ ”Weren’t things supposed to be different? Wasn’t the rise of women in the workplace going to usher in a new era where two career couples would flourish side by side, sharing household and family duties and a more balanced life? “People used to say that men needed a wife at home and a wife at the office — the traditional secretary,” Ms. Kanter said. “Now women need the same thing: an assistant at work and a stay-at-home husband or at least a husband who’s very flexible and supportive. Anyone who hopes to be a corporate chief executive needs a big support system.”

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

There are prominent exceptions, and there are male C.E.O.’s who have wives with their own successful careers. Meg Whitman, newly installed as C.E.O. at Hewlett-Packard, is married to Griffith Harsh IV, a widely published and highly regarded neurosurgeon on the faculty at Stanford Medical School, who has pursued an obviously demanding and successful career. The couple raised two sons. Still, Dr. Harsh left the Harvard faculty and a prominent position at Massachusetts General Hospital to relocate to California when Ms. Whitman was named chief executive of eBay earlier in her career.Some of the women executives Mr. Zweigenhaft studied “are married to high-powered partners who are also C.E.O.’s or senior executives,” he said, such as Laura Sen (chief executive of BJ’s Wholesale Club), who was married to C. Michael Egan (chief of the biotech company Transmolecular until his death in 2009).There are very few true house husbands, men with no career outside the home. Nearly all husbands of chief executives have had some occupation, even if it is modest compared to their wives. Some husbands retire early. Frank Fiorina, who worked for many years at AT&T, took early retirement in 1998 to better support the career of his wife, Carly Fiorina, who became chief executive of Hewlett-Packard the next year and subsequently ran for the United States Senate. Ms. Fiorina had no children, but helped raise his two children from a previous marriage. And some C.E.O.’s find additional support from other family members. Ms. Rometty is described as especially close to her mother, whom she brought to this year’s I.B.M. centennial celebration.Among male chief executives, the supportive spouse still seems the norm.But there are some signs of change. Steve Tappin, author of “The Secrets of C.E.O.’s” (NB Publishing, 2008) and a management consultant with executive clients, said that top executives with high-powered spouses — or even no spouses — can now build “a great support system as long as they’re not financially constrained. They need life assistants and deep levels of support from friends and confidantes. It can even save them time not having to sustain a relationship.”But one thing that hasn’t changed is the all-out commitment to work and career needed from men and women who want to reach the top. “This is why so many women bail out,” Mr. Zweigenhaft said. “It’s not a life they want. But some do, and they’re finding the partners they need: men who are comfortable with the role of the supportive spouse.”Ms. Kanter said: “We’re at an odd inflection point. We’re still trying to figure out what it means for men and women to be peers, or to shift roles from time to time. Should one career come first? Couples are still struggling to work that out.”
Continue reading the main story






